Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Dorcas Misango¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a data set that includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area in (2019).

# to category

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

after the dataset was cleaned, I was left with 183412 rows and 10 columns:

  • duration_sec (int).
  • start_time (datetime).
  • end_time (datetime).
  • start_station_name (object)
  • end_station_name (object)
  • bike_id (object)
  • user_type (category)
  • member_birth_year
  • member_gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip(object)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

the main feature of interest for this exploration is where are most trips taken, at what time and by who

  • start time : what time do people prefer when going out for bike riding
  • start_station_name: where is the most popular start station
  • user type and member gender: which category uses bikes more

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • All remaining features, since not neeeded columns were dropped during the cleaning process.

lets separate the days, months and hour of the start time into new columns and also change the duration seconds to minutes. This will make it easier to explore the data

# new useful columns

#start_time broken down into months, days and hours
bike_df['start_month'] = bike_df.start_time.dt.month
bike_df['start_day'] = bike_df.start_time.dt.weekday 
bike_df['start_hour'] = bike_df.start_time.dt.hour

# from end_time
bike_df['end_hour'] = bike_df.end_time.dt.hour

# from duration_sec to duration_minutes
bike_df['duration_minutes'] = bike_df['duration_sec']/60

# 2. Create ages
bike_df['age'] = bike_df['member_birth_year'].apply(lambda x: 2019 - x)

def x_y_t(xL,yL,title):
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xL)
    plt.ylabel(yL)
    color = sb.color_palette()[2]

In [10]:
# histogram with logarithmic scale transformation

tick_locs = [1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000]

x_y_t('duration_minutes','Count','Duration Histogram')

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

duration_minutes

most rides were extremely short and took about (4-6) minutes. Very few rides lasted more than one hour.

start_time

Based on the day: most rides were on Thursdays and Tuesdays. the days with the least amount of rides were Saturday and Sunday Based on starting hour: the distribution is roughly bimodal (has two peaks) at 8 am and 5pm.

end_time Based on ending hour: the distribution is roughly bimodal (has two peaks) at 8 am and 5pm. This could be because most rides didt last more than an hour.

user_type

The majority of bike users in 2019 were subscribers and most of the riders were also males (74.7%). A logarithmic scale transformation was applied on duration_minutes and age hist plots, because the data follows an approximately log-normal distribution, lots of points with low values, with a very long tail of data points with large values

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

yes there were some operations done to tidy up the dataset: new columns were crated:

  • from start_time - start_hour, start_day and start_hour
  • from end_time - end_hour
  • duration seconds converted to minutes For the gender groups, there is a 'Other' category. Before I confirm the information, I will keep them in the dataset.
